    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. it actually works better than a simple threshold filter sometimes, but i'm worried some of the extreme outliers are actually important shifts and not just errors. can u make it a bit more robust? maybe use something that looks at the rate of change between readings so it doesn't just delete a legitimate sudden spike?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right; a simple threshold can discard real rapid thermal shifts, so checking the rate of change is a much better approach. This script filters out any reading where the temperature drops or rises faster than a reasonable limit (e.g., 1°C per minute) *and* falls outside your safety bounds. By combining these two checks, you'll keep genuine fast events while still removing sensor faults.\n\n```python\ndata = [...]  # List of (timestamp, temp) tuples\nmin_temp, max_temp, max_rate = -1, 25, 1.0\n\ndef check_rate(data_point, time_diff):\n    return abs(data_point[1] - prev_temp) / time_diff <= max_rate\n\nfiltered = []; prev_temp = data[0][1]\nfor i in range(1, len(data)):\n    dt = (data[i][0] - data[i-1][0]).total_seconds()\n    if check_rate(data[i], dt) and min_temp <= data[i][1] <= max_temp:\n        filtered.append(data[i])\n    prev_temp = data[i][1]\n```\n\nRunning this in a loop ensures only stable, physically plausible data points pass through",
      "source": "target",
